## CI/CD

### 1. CI vs CD vs Continuous Deployment
- **CI (Continuous Integration):** devs merge code often, automated build + tests run on every commit
- **Continuous Delivery:** code is always in a deployable state, but release to prod needs manual approval
- **Continuous Deployment:** every passing change goes to prod automatically, no manual step

### 2. Explain your CI/CD pipeline flow
- Code pushed → triggers pipeline
- Build → run unit tests → static code/security scan
- Package (e.g., Docker image) → push to registry
- Deploy to staging → run integration tests
- Manual/auto approval → deploy to production
- Post-deploy checks (health check, smoke test)

### 3. Stages in CI/CD pipeline
- Source (checkout code)
- Build
- Test (unit/integration)
- Code quality/security scan
- Package/Artifact creation
- Deploy (staging → prod)
- Post-deployment verification

### 4. Problems CI/CD solves
- Removes manual, error-prone deployments
- Catches bugs early (before prod)
- Faster, consistent releases
- Easy rollback
- Better visibility into what changed and when

### 5. Troubleshooting pipeline failures
- Check pipeline logs first (which stage failed)
- Reproduce locally if possible
- Check recent code/config changes
- Check environment/credentials/permissions issues
- Fix, re-run, and add a check to prevent recurrence

### 6. Example: GitLab pipeline failure and fix
- Example: pipeline failed due to expired runner token/cache corruption
- Steps: checked job logs → found auth/cache error → cleared cache/regenerated token → pipeline passed
- Added monitoring/alert so it's caught earlier next time

### 7. Git branching strategy
- Common: **Git Flow** or **trunk-based development**
- Git Flow: main, develop, feature/*, release/*, hotfix/*
- Trunk-based: short-lived feature branches, merge to main frequently

### 8. Managing Git branches
- Naming convention (feature/, bugfix/, hotfix/)
- Delete branches after merge
- Protect main/master branch (no direct push)
- Regular cleanup of stale branches

### 9. Backup before deleting stale branches
- Yes — check if merged first (`git branch --merged`)
- Tag or archive before deleting if unsure
- Deleted branches still recoverable via reflog for a short time

### 10. Code review and merge approval process
- Developer raises PR/MR with description
- At least 1-2 reviewers approve
- CI checks (build/tests) must pass
- No direct merge to main — only via approved PR
- Squash/merge commit based on team convention

### 11. Git Merge vs Git Rebase
- **Merge:** combines branches, keeps full history, creates a merge commit
- **Rebase:** moves commits on top of another branch, creates linear history
- Use **merge** for shared/public branches
- Use **rebase** for cleaning up local feature branch before merging

### 12. What is Git
- Distributed version control system
- Tracks code changes, enables collaboration
- Every developer has full history locally

### 13. Declarative vs Scripted Pipeline (Jenkins)
- **Declarative:** structured, easier syntax (`pipeline { stages {...} }`), recommended for most cases
- **Scripted:** Groovy-based, more flexible/complex, full programming control

