## Shell Scripting & Linux

### 1. Linux commands used regularly
- `ls`, `cd`, `grep`, `awk`, `sed`, `top`/`htop`, `ps`, `df`, `du`, `chmod`, `chown`, `systemctl`, `journalctl`, `netstat`/`ss`, `curl`

### 2. Automation tasks via shell scripting
- Log cleanup scripts
- Health check/monitoring scripts
- Backup automation
- Deployment helper scripts

### 3. Are scripts used by team? Impact
- Yes — shared scripts save manual repetitive work
- Reduced deployment time / manual errors
- Standardized process across team members

### 4. Troubleshooting Linux server issues
- Check system resources: `top`, `free`, `df -h`
- Check logs: `/var/log/`, `journalctl`
- Check running services: `systemctl status`
- Check network: `netstat`, `ping`, `curl`

### 5. Example shell script for real-time problem
- Example: script to auto-detect disk usage > 80% and send alert/email
- Example: script to rotate/clean old logs automatically via cron
- Example: script to check service health and auto-restart if down

